Start with the fundamentals of how databases handle concurrency and recovery, then move toward the specific data structures that make them fast. For a weekend dive, you want to focus on the interplay between **transactional isolation** and **physical storage**—specifically how a database ensures that your data is safe and consistent even when multiple users are writing at once.

[Transactionally Staged Job Drains in Postgres](https://brandur.org/job-drain) provides a high-leverage entry point by showing these internals in action. It explains **MVCC (Multi-Version Concurrency Control)** through the lens of a "job drain" pattern, where the database must keep uncommitted changes invisible to other workers. This illustrates the "visibility" problem that MVCC solves: rather than locking every row, the database keeps multiple versions of data so readers don't block writers.

To understand why we need these mechanisms for long-running operations, [Sagas](https://www.cs.cornell.edu/andru/cs711/2002fa/reading/sagas.pdf) is the classic paper on managing atomicity and resource locking. It’s essential for understanding the trade-offs of **Write-Ahead Logging (WAL)** and recovery; if a transaction fails halfway through, the system relies on these logs to ensure it can either roll back or "compensate" for the partial work.

